{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_jasmine_ver01/data/sn78000533/00340580345/1945122701/0381.xml":{"full_text":"\u25a0W!\ncfc\nghT\nA--\ns.\nfe'\n\u2022j.\u00ab\n7 OFFICIAL ORGAN V\nNATIONAL BROTHERHOOD OF\nOPERATIVE POTTERS\nVOL. XLIX, NO. 35\n5\n'\u2022ft?\nJ*.\u2019-us\n1\nn\u00abp^\nWe were very pleased to welcome a\ncommittee from Local Union 99,\nClarksburg, who were here to study\nour setup in the print shop. The vis\nitors were impressed with our system\nand indicated they would recommend\nthe same plan for Clarksburg. The\nparty included Mrs. Doyer, Mrs. Patsy\nand Augustine Mazzie. The latter\nasked many questions regarding the\nAluminum Therapy treatments which\nhe witnessed for the first time.\n's t.\nSanta Claus paid us a visit on De\ncember 24 and distributed our vaca\ntion checks. While speaking of vaca\nv tion checks we might take this means\nto answer the inquiry frbm Local\nW* Union 124 in regards to members tak\ning the time off. We are one hundred\nper cent in accord with your proposal.\nEverett Wyatt, cup jiggerman from\nErwin, Tenm, is our latest arrival. We\nwelcomp Bro. Wyatt and hope he\nlikes it here\u2014at least he got a chance\nto see what a snowfall means up\nNorth.\nThe latest dust counts in the sand\nand bisque kiln show a count of 2.08\n(Turn to Page Two)\nPrice Fixing Acts*\nShould Go. FTQ\nTeUs Congress\nWashington\u2014(FP).\u2014American con\n/sumers, being taken for millions of\ndollars of hard-earned cash each\n7^ year by greedy retailers, got a glimpse\nof hope Dec. 14 when the Federal\nTrade Commisison recommended that\nCongress repeal the Miller-Tydings\nenabling act.\n't The Miller-Tydings act permits the\nstates to pass laws allowing manu\nfacturers to set their own retail prices\non trade-marked goods. All but three\n'states\u2014Vermont, Texas, Missouri and\nthe District of Columbia have given\nin to the retail lobby.\nOriginally adopted as a means of\nhelping the little storekeeper against\n^the competition of the chain operator,\nit has actually choked off competition\nand blocked the free enterprise prin\nciple of supply and demand.\nIn sending its report to Congress\nrecommending repeal of the price\nfixing act, the FTC has joined the\nDept, of Justice and the old temporary\nNatl. Economic Committee and the I\nNatl. Defense Advisory Committee in\ncondemning the law.\nMaintenance of minimum resale\nprices, the FTC report said, \u201chas been\nmore extensively applied in the drug,\ntoilet goods, cosmetics, liquor and\nsporting goods, trades than in any\nother lines covered in this inquiry.\nThis is due in part to the individuality\n(Turn to Page Six)\n.{Legal Analysis Of The President\u2019s\n\u00aeNew Cooling-Off Period Proposal\nBy LEONARD B. BOUDIN\n/For Federated Press\nOnce again as before the war Con\ngress has before it a bill providing\nfor cooling-off periods during which\nlabor may pot strike. There are three\nimportant differences, however. The\nbill is introduced at the suggestion\nof the President it is not supported\n\u00abby the war emergency which existed\nt/3n the earlier case and it springs\n\u2019/directly from the government\u2019s own\nfailure to cope with the primarily\n5'i\neconomic causes of current strikes.\nThe Norton bill introduced in the\nHouse gives the secretary of labor the\n/power to certify the existence of a\nl^labor dispute involving a threatened\nstoppage of work \u201cseriously affecting\nI national public interest and af\n^''vfecting interstate or foreign com\nmierce, or the national defense.\u201d With\n4 in five days from the certification, the\nII President may appoint a board to\ninvestigate and report on the dispute.\nit must submit its report to the Presi\n|r. dent within 20 days from its appoint\nII. pnent unless both parties and the\nI si*ent a*ree an \u00a9rtension of\nThe proposed law would place the\nfollowing limitations upon the disput-\nIB ing parties during the period from the\ncertification until five days after the\nboard submit* its report to the Presi-\nFft\n.W\nFirst Edition Of New\nPublication At Buffalo\nShop Meets Approval\nWEEKLY ISSUE OF \u201cPOTTERY POST\u201d\nTENDS TO PROMOTE MORE FRIENDLY\nRELATIONSHIP BERT CLARK, EDITOR\nBuffalo, N. Y.\u2014Any news that comes from Buffalo these\ndays can pertain to only one thing\u2014SNOW. We have been snow\nbound for the past several days, having had a 48-inch snowfal\nin twenty-four hours. X\u2019Ji\nOfficers were elected at otir meeting on Dec. 21 and President\nCarl Heintz was returned to office for his seventh consecutive\nterm. This is a record at Local Union 76 and speaks well for the\nwonderful job he has done. Others returned for another term\ninclude Alphonse Weiczorek, vice president Bert Clark, finan\ncial secretary, and Oscar Dale, recording secretary. The new of\nficers elected are Edward Scuster, inspector Harold Jergenson,\nguard John Urban, trustee.\nST\ns\n1\n59\u00bb\u00ab.\nA\nAsk Increase To\nMeet Increased\nCost Of Living\nColorado Springs, Colo.\u2014(FP).\nWage boosts for the nation\u2019s ship\nbuilders to help them meet the in\ncreased cost of living were demanded\nby AFL and CIO union leaders here\nat the Natl. Shipbuilding Conference,\nwhich opened Dec. 4.\nRepresentatives of labor, manage\nment and government were in atten\ndance at the meeting, the first held\nsince 1942 when the Natl. War Labor\nBoard took over wage reviews in the\nshipbuilding industry. Government\nRep. E. A. McMillan, chairman of the\nShipbuilders Stabilization Committee,\nwas named permanent chairman of the\nconference and a working committee\nof 36 regular members and 36 alter\nnates was set up\nA 17%c hourly wage increase\n\u201cacross the board\u201d and a 30% wage\nincrease to make up for overtime pay\nlost through the reduction of the 48\nhour workweek were proposed by\nPres. John Green of Industrial Union\nof Marine A Shipbuilding Workers.\nPres. John P. -Frey. o\u00a3 the AFL\nMetal Trades Dept, said he would\nnot request any specific amount as the\nincrease in wages he believed should\nbe granted at the conference. \u201cWe\nare going to ask this conference to\nrestore to the shipyard worker the\nreal wage he had in. 1941,\u201d he said.\nGreen charged that shipyard work\ners have lost almost four months\nsalary to date because the cost of liv\ning was not shoved back to the March\n1942 level as the late Pres. Roosevelt\npromised it would be. On the basis of\nthe President\u2019s assurance the shipyard\nworkers accepted an 8c increase in\nstead of abiding by the escalator\nclauses of the four zone standards\nshipbuilding agreement, Green pointed\nout.\n\u201cTo date, through December of 1\n1945, the shipyard workers will have\nlost almost four months salary be\ncause of this failure of the promise\n(Turn to Page Five)\nNEW OFFICERS NAMED\nBY LOCAL UNION 178\nSebring, Ohio.\u2014The following offi\ncers were elected by Local Union 178,\nArtware Workers, for the coming\nterm: President, Clarence Bostwick\nvice president, Warren Hendershot\nrecording secretary, John Dorff\ntreasurer, Robert Webb financial sec\nretary, George Court defense secre\ntary, James Simpson guard, Mrs.\nReedy inspector, Frieda Snyder trus\ntee, Alden McClennan.\u2014O. C. 178.\ndent: (1) the working conditions in\neffect prior to the dispute must con\ntinued, (2) no strike or lockout may\nbe called or assisted by advice, strike\nbenefits or otherwise.\nThe main objection to the Norton\nbill is that it menaces the fundamen\ntal right to strike. That right was se\ncured by labor only after years of\nbitter struggle. For many years\nstrikes and labor organizations were\nheld by statute and judicial decision\nto be criminal conpiracies. Today the\nrights of self organization and col\nlective bargaining are firmly estab\nlished by such statutes as the Norris\nLaGuardia act and the Wagner act.\nIt would be a gross regression\ncurtail this fundamental method\nlabor\u2019s protest.\nto\nOf\nIS\nIn addition, the right to strike\nclearly essential to the exercise\nthe right of collective bargaining. The\nlast right is meaningless if workers\ncannot implement their refusal to ac\ncept an employer\u2019s terms by a con\ncerted refusal to work. To argue that\nthe bill merely suspends the right for\n30 days is not to deny the evil but to\nsuggest that it is one of short dura\ntion. Even this may not be true, since\nthe 30-day period my be the crucial\none in collective bargaining.\nof\ncause\nThe bill disregards the real\n(Turn to Page Six) v\nF.R\nReal Holiday\nSpirit Shown\nBy Company\nEmployees Guests Of\nFirm At Xmas Dinner\nTrenton,' N. J.\u2014Members of Local\nUnion 210, employees of the Stevens\nPeterson Company, manufacturers of\nart and novelty ware, were guests of\nthe firm at a turkey dinner served\nat the plant on Dec. 22.\nThe dinner was served at 12 noon\nand the menu can best 6e described as\nincluding everything from soup to\nnuts. First Vice- President Wheatley\nand Organizer Jame^ Solon were spec\nial guests for the occassion and both\nofficials paid tribute in their remarks\nfor the harmonious relationship which\nexisted between the firm and the\n(Turn to Page Five)\nGI Publication\nShows Anti-Union\nStories A Flop\nRome, Italy\u2014(FP). Failure of\npropaganda stories from the U. S. to\nconvert soldiers in Italy to anti-union\nism is reflected in letters appearing\nin Mail Call, the column in The Stars\nA Stripes Mediterranean, published:\nhere, where men sound off about\nthings.\nThe firsi blast which blamed the\nNew York longshoremen\u2019s strike for\ndelaying the return of troops made\nan impression, but not much\u2014and it\ndidn\u2019t last long. Only two soldiers\nwere enough impressed by the propa\nganda to write The Stars A Stripes\nabout it. A number of GIs came to\nthe rescue of unions, however.\nA letter signed by four members\nof the 686th Ordnance Ammo Co. said:\n\u201cThese men were only using one of\nthe guaranteed liberties of the con\nstitution. We think it is only fair that\nthese men should have an increase in\nwages.\u201d By this time the editors of\nThe Stars A Stripes were giving top\nplay to statements by the Greater\nNew York Industrial Union Council\nand by the Natl. Maritime Union ex\nposing the fraud behind the attempt\nto blame demobilization delays on la\nbor.\nSgt. John L. Laverty wrote to Mail\nCall: \u201cMaybe you realize that there\nare many veterans participating in\nthepe strikes which are their last\nlegal means to force the employers\nto keep their wartime promises. Notj\n(Turn to Page Two)\nTruman Asks Full\nEmployment Bill\nWashington\u2014(FP). In identical\nletters to Sen. Robert F. Wagner (D,\nN. Y.) and Rep. Carter Manasco (D,\nAla.), Pres. Truman Dec. 20 called for\npassage by Congress of the modified\nSenate version of the full employment\nbill.\nTruman said the Senate version\nmodified the language of the original\nmeasure \u201cbut did not remove its es\nsential provisions. On Dec. 14, how\never, the House sent to conference a\nwholly new measure lacking the es\nsential features of the full employ\nment bill as passed by the Senate.\n\u201cIn my opinion, no bill which pro\nvides substantially less than the Sen\nate version can efficiently accomp\nlish the purposes intended. I hope that\nthe Congress will adopt a bill substan\ntially in the form passed by the Sen\nate/\nTruman said.\n*i\u00ab\nV1R\nOe Putters Herald\n\u00bb*4\nCOOLING OFF PERIOD\nEAST LIVERPOOL, OHIO, THURSDAY, DECEMBER 27, 1945\nNewspaper\nGuild Backs\nAlso Gives Support\n\u25a0Xp Uniogi Steel Workers\nDetroit\u2014(FP). Support of the\nGeneral Motors strike with cash, pic\nketing and publicity was urged on all\nmembers of the Newspaper Guild of\nDetroit in a resolution unanimously\nadopted by the quarterly membership\nmeeting Dee. 12. Together with this\naid to the United rAuto Workers in\ntheir fight against the largest and\npossiblyJ\u00bbughest -American industrial\ncorporation, support was voted in the\nUnited Steelworkers drive for a $2\na day wage raise.\nPres. Don Schram of the Detroit\nguild reviewed a very satisfactory\nyear of wage raises and other union\npapers. Of the 770 active members 139\ngains on the three Detroit daily\nare still on military leave. The 301\nnew members signed up during the\nyear represent a net gain of 91 the\nrest being a byproduct of the high\nlabor turnover in Detroit newspaper\nwork. Of the 631 on the job 394 are\nin good standing compared with 287 a\nyear earlier.\nThe guild (union) shop was con\nceded by the Detroit Free Press\n(Knight) management and a general\nraise ranging from $5 a week to -?9\nhas been offered bu( turned down by\nthe Union which thinks something bet\nter is to be had for a little pressure.\nMaintenance of membership, premium\nfor night work and a better holiday\nclause as well as increased minimums\nin 21 classifications were also won.\nThe Detroit Times (Hearst) unit\n(Turn to Page Two)\nArfware Workers\nAt Chester Plant\nForm New Local\nAnother new local is added this\nweek to the official directory of the\nNational Brotherhood of Operative\nPotters\u2014Local Union No. 212, Art\nware Workers, Chester, W. Va.\nThe new unit in the Brotherhood\nchain comprises the employees of the\nContinental Kilns who were formerly\naffiliated with Local Union No. 209.\nLouis Sanford was elected president\nof the new local and will have as his\naides Robert Pennybaker, vice presi\ndent Kathryn Murray, recording sec\nretary Twyla Sayre, financial secre\ntary Joseph Arcuragi, treasurer\nBlair Sanford, inspector Hershel\nStover, guard trustees, Frank Mount\nford, Regina Dickey and Adda Ward.\nThe Chester plant manufactures a\nhigh grade of art ware and has added\nmany new employees to their payroll\nsince signing a working agreement\nwith the Brotherhood in November.\nSixth Vice President George Turn\ner installed the officers at the first\nmeeting of the local.\nFactory Jobs Drop Sharply\nIn 2 Industrial States\nPhiladelphia (ILNS). Contract\ncancellations after V-J Day caused\nsubstantial drops in factory jobs in\nthe big industrial states of Pennsyl\nvania, ahd Deleware, the Federal Re\nserve Bank of Philadelphia reports.\nIn Pennsylvania, factory employment\ndeclined 7 percent, from August to\nSeptember.\nThe decrease in employment and a\nfurther reduction in the work week\nin September were reflected in a 10\npercent decline in both total\nand total wage payments.\naS\n11^\nt.\nOutlook Good\nFor '46, Says\nErwin Scribe\n\u201cSunshine City\u201d Has\nFirst Snow In Years\nErwin, Tenn. It has been some\ntime since the trade has heard any\nnews from Erwin, Tenn., so thia is\na little reminder that we are still in\nthe trade. Known as the Sunshine\nCity throughout the trade, a spot\nwhere ideal weather prevails the year\nround, the climate at this time of\nyear has changed a little. At present\nwe are having severe cold weather\nwith a little snow and ice thrown in\nfor good measure. z\nThe plant here is wording full\ntime and from all indications a full\ntime schedule lies ahead for 1946.\nSome of the members have managed\nto take a few days to go hunting and\nall report the \u201climit\u201d for their day\u2019s\nefforts in the woods. One of our fin\nishers was reported as using a club\nin preference to a gun while chasing\nthe bunnies. How about that Fred?\nQuite a number of the boys have\nreturned from the service and are\nback working at the plant. These in-,\nelude Carl and Guy Foster who saw\nconsiderable service in the Pacific\nwhile members of the Marine Corps\nHobart and Earl Miller, Glavis Pow\ners, Horace Adkins Carl McCurray,\nClaude Brackings, Cliff Campbell,\n\u201cGriz\u201d Engle, Millard Engle, Warren\nHampton, Paul Perdue and Elmer Bai\nley. We welcome our buddies back\nand are proud of their wonderful rec\nord- Z,\nBro. \"Bill Campbell has been' off\nfor the past several weeks having un\ndergone a major operation. Latest re\nports indicated he is well on the road\nof recovery.\nThe following officers were elected\nfor the first six months: President,\nJohn Reynolds vice president, Fur\nman McIntosh recording secretary,\nM. B. Lafrs financial secretary, James\nSanders treasurer, Chester Lozier\ndefense secretary, Nettie Ford trus\ntee, J. Q. Engle statistician, Henry\nBruce.\nThese officers will be installed at\nour next meeting and we sincerely:\nhope they will have the whole-hearted\ncooperation of the entire membership\nduring their reign in office.\n103.\nSeek Injunctions\nAgainst Pickets\nAt General Motors\nDetroit\u2014(FP). Reaching for a\nlegal brickbat to hurl at strikers who\nhave shut down General Motors plants\nthroughout the nation since Nov. 21,\nGM filed petitions asking injunctions\nagainst picketing at its Cleveland and\nChicago factories.\n\u201cNo progress\u201d was reported in con\ntinuing negotiations here between cor\nporation and union representatives on\ndemands for a 30% pay increase.\nEmerging from wage talks Dec. 13,\nVice Pres. Walter P. Reuther con\ndemned the \u201cgutter ethics\u201d of GM of\nficials. Asked to comment on GM\u2019s\nlegal move, Reuther said the firm\ncould get all the injunctions it wanted\n\u2019\u2019but they won\u2019t make automobiles, nor\nwill the judges who grant the injunc\ntions.\u201d\nIn its Cleveland court action GM\ncomplained that pickets had kept non\nstriking employes from entering its\nFisher plant and also accused the\nunionists of \u201cdisorderly\u201d conduct. The\nCleveland Industrial Union Council\ncountered with a charge that GM had\nordered its non-production employes\nto report to work in an attempt to\nprovoke violence.\nThe GM petition filed in superior\ncourt in Cook county (Chicago) said\nthat \u201cthe unionists engaged -in mass\npicketing, placed obstructions across\u25a0\nplant entrances and inflicted bodily!\nharm on employes.\u201d\nHopes for an early settlement at\nthe Ford Motor Co., were apparently\ndashed after the company announced\nit was not prepared to grant, ftny\nwage increases at this time..\nUtility Workers\nWin 15% Increase\nSan Diego, Calif.\u2014(FP).\u2014A will\ningness by labor and management to\n\u201csplit the difference\u201d in collective\nbargaining has resulted in wage in\ncreases amounting to (450,000 annual\nly for 1,200 employes of the San Die\ngo Gas A Electric Co.,\nThe union, Local 465, Inti. Bro. of\nElectrical Workers (AFL), had de\nmanded a 20% pay boost at the outset\nof negotiations.\nAfter four months of bargaining\nthe company granted, and the union\nmembership accepted, a 15% raise re\ntroactive to mid-August. Unpsual fea\nture of the settlement was that al\nthough the union has jurisdiction over\nonly mechanical employes, numbering\nabout 800, the utility voluntarily\nplied the same\noffice workers.\nhours increases\nW\u2019&'\n3 \u2019A \u00bbU.\nC.\nap\n400\nto its\n.^l\nSchwellenbach\nUrges Holding of\nPrice Controls^\nThe cabinet members warned that\n\u201cif American labor is faced with a\nrise in prices month after month just\nas the war ends, industrial unrest\nwill inevitably increase. This is espec\nially important because pay envelopes\nare shrinking. Millions of our people\nare earning less money now than they\ndid six months ago and more oL.them\nwill have less to spend in the next\nsix months.\u201d\nNot only are pay wieloptAi shrink\ning, he said, \u201cbut fewer people are\ngoing to be at work and less money\nis coming home to the family. Over\n2.5 million production workers have\nbeen laid off in the heavy industries\nsince V-E Day and 1.6 million since\nV-J Day alone.\u201d After recalling that\nby spring more servicemen will be\nhome and their furlough pay will be\nused up, and \u201cunemployment will be\na more serious problem than it is\nnow,\u201d Schwellenbach said \"with such\na situation as this we simply cannot\nallow prices of living essentials to go\nup any more.\n\u201cMost of all,\u201d he emphasized, \u201cwe\ncannot permit rents to run wild. These\ndangers are very real indeed. They\nbegin with the simple fact that there\nare shortages of many kinds of\ngoods. If price and rent controls are\nremoved, the cost of living would go\nthrough the roof in six months.\u201d\nSchwellenbach found the mgsfc ser\n(Turn to Page Tvto)\nBegin Repairs Now, i\nHome Owners Urged\nWashington, D. C.\u2014(ILNS).\u2014Home\nowners wishing to make repairs and\nalterations essential for safety and\nprotection of property should begin\nsuch work as soon as possible if the\navailability of materials in their lo\ncalities will permit, it was recommen\nded by Clarence W. Farrier, director,\nTechnical Division of the National\nHousing Agency.\nMEMBEB\nINTERNATIONAL LABOR\nNEWS SERVICE\nS: K\nTrenton Potters Elect\nA.\nJamieson, PresidentI.\u2022'\nOf Local Union No. 45\nFIRM GIVES EACH EMPLOYEE TURKEY\nFOR CHRISTMAS WILL HOLD SOCIAL\n^FOLLOWING MEETING ON JANUARY 4TH\nTrenton, N. J.\u2014I^ocal Union 45 elected the following of\nficers to serve for the first six months of the new year: President\nA. Jamieson vice president, R. Smith financial secretary, E.\nWatson recording secretary, Lance Ansell treasurer, J. Richards\ninspector, J. Glover guard, Herbert Meyer trustee, P. Duboski.\nConferees will be named the first of the year.\nFourth Vice President Charles Zimmer reported a meeting of\nthe firm and conference committee held on Dec. 17th at which\ntime a 10-cent raise was granted on all jets 4 cents on the Troy\nreverse trap, and 3 cents on the Numode wash down. Many other\nlower paid items were discussed and will be taken up on Dec. 27th.\nWashington\u2014(FP).\u2014 Full support\nof price and rent control was voiced\nDec. 19 by Sec. *bf Labor Lewis\nSchwellenbach in a statement before\nthe Senate small business committee.\nSchwellenbach said he wanted price\ncontrol continued \u201cuntil reconversion\nhas brought an ample supply of goods\nback onto retailers\u2019 shelves,\u201d and that\nhe favored rent control \u201cuntil the con\nstruction industry has been able to\nprovide housing for at least a good\nshare of the millions of families who\ntoday are looking for a place to live.\u201d\nJob Opportunity For Southern\nVeterans 72-Hour Week For $200\nBy ELIZABETH GREEN\nFederated Press\nWinston-Salem N, C.\u2014(FP).\u2014Un\nderlying the unemployment that set\ntled on this town after V-J Day is the\nsouth\u2019s notorious low wage system,\nwhich came through the war unscath\ned.\nEight thousand workers in this city\nof. 95,0()0 were laid off when three\nwtfr plants closed down at the end of\nthe war, Two thousand commuted here\nfrom nearby communities and of the\nremaining 6,000, about half are still\ndrawing unemployment compensation.\nWhat happened to the rest is un\nknown.\nWages being offeree^ men run from\n50c to 60c an hour, according to Sec.\nTreas. Sy Chisholm of the Winston\nSalem Central Labor Union, and re\nturning veterans are dismayed and\nangered by the socalled job opportun\nities awaiting them here. One labor\norganizer told me of a nonunion vet\neran who reported that he'd just been\noffered a 72-hour job for $25 a week\nand that he\u2019d \u201cbe damned if he was\ngoing to take it. The unions should\ncrack down on some of these people.\u201d\nAccording to Harry J. Krusz, gen\neral manager of the local chamber of\ncommerce there is a shortage of skill\ned and common labor in Winston\nSalem. Chisolm reports, however, ttmt\n*fe-\nBy HAROLD PREECE\nTallahassee, Fla.\u2014(FP).\u2014 Fearful\nlest the anti-closed shop Florid* right\nto-work amendment be rubbed out in\nU. S. supreme court proceedings in\nstituted by both the AFL and CIO,\nState Atty. Gen. J. Tom Watson is\nseeking to have its main provision\nwritten into Pres. Truman\u2019s fact-find^\ning legislation now pending before\nCongress.\nWatson, generally regarded in Flor\nida as \u201cduPont\u2019s man,\u201d revealed that\nhe had written Sen. Elbert D. Thomas\n(D, Utah), chairman of the Senate\ncommittee on education and labors\nurging amendments that would give\ncongressional sanction to the state\u2019s\nright-to-work amendment and to pro\nvide for court reviews of decisions\nreached by socalled fact-finding\nboards.\nThis means that if one of these\nBoards accidentally decided in favor\nof a union against an employer, the\nway would be open for corporation\ncontrolled lawyers like ^\u2019atson to go\ninto a federal court ana nave the de\ncision set aside.\nThe proposal, too, is simply a new\nvariation on an old strategy used by\nthe southern open shop bloc in Con\ngress to tack on the right-to-work\nproposal as amendments to other bills.\n(Tum to Page Six)\nhalf the machinists laid off by the\nNatl. Carbon Co., are still looking\nfor work.\nThe Food Tobacco A Agricultural\nWorkers discloses that Nazi war pris\noners are still working in the tobac\nco leaf houses, although their remov\nal has been promised by the War\nDept., within a month. Management\u2019^\nexplanation for the use of POWs is\nthat nobody else wants the jobs. FTA\nsays: \u201cThat\u2019s hard, nasty work that\u00ab\nnobody wants to do for 50c an hour.\u201d\nWhile 30 to 45 small new busineasfes\nhave been opened this year and the\nDuplan Corp., is building a $1 million\nnylon processing plant expected to\ngive employment to the better part\nof a thousand, this still does not add\nup to nearly enough jobs for the\n11,000 boys who went into the army\nand the 11,000 more who left to woric\nelsewhere, most of whom are expect*\ned to return here.\nA period of business expansion i*\nahead, the C. of C. claims, naming\nlabor and transportation facilities as\nit special inducements to attract new\nindustry here. Both are on the sur\nface rather doubtful inducement*.\nThe main railroad line is off in\nGreensboro, some 30 miles away, and\nmost communities can now beast of a\nlarge labor supply. If the C. of C. had\n(Tttfx to Pggt\n1\n$2.00 PER YEAR 1\nBro. Frank Shek received his dis\ncharge from the army recently and\nexpects to be back with us soon.\nBros. Joseph Abrams, Joseph Hawks\nand Tom Ward are on the sick list but\nwe hope not too sick to enjoy the\nholidays.\nThe Trenton Potteries Company\nagain gave each employee a turkey\nfor Christmas. We extend our thanks\nto the officials for their generosity,\nand wish them continued success for\nthe new year.\nDue to various circumstances we\ndid not meet on Dec. 14 and the so\ncial which was to follow our meeting\nhas been postponed until our next\nmeeting on January 4. The commit\ntee promises to go all out in their\nefforts to make the first party in\nthe new year, bigger and better than\nany we have yet held.\nThe Executive Board, First Vice\nPresident Wheatley and Second Vice\nPresident Frank Hull sent cards wish\ning the members a Merry Christinas\nand a Happy New Year, while Fourth\nVice President Zimmer expressed his\nwishes personally for which we thank\nthem and wish them the same.\u2014O. C.\nWonts Open Shop\nClause\u201dAdded To\u00bb\nPresident's Bill 5\n\"\u2022^1\n\u2018\u2018M\nIff\ni\u00bb\nl'/,\nif:\nKi\nW\nI\n7'^'\ni -i\nA","height":"26172","width":"20052"}}
